## Why This Is Asked

Tests the ability to translate a threat model into Azure‑native controls, tying identity lifecycle (PIM/JIT, minimal RBAC) to network segmentation (Private Endpoints, NSGs) and automated IR (Defender for Cloud, Sentinel) with verifiable rollback.

## Key Concepts

- Just‑In‑Time (PIM) and ephemeral workload identities
- Least‑privilege RBAC scoped to resources
- Private Endpoints and network segmentation (NSGs, subnets)
- Defender for Cloud and Azure Sentinel integration
- Automated containment playbooks and rollback procedures

## Code Example

```javascript
// PIM‑like pseudo‑API to request ephemeral access (illustrative)
async function requestEphemeralAccess(role, resourceId) {
  const approval = await pim.request({ role, resourceId, ttlSeconds: 3600 });
  if (!approval.approved) throw new Error('PIM approval failed');
  return approval.credentials;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you test the rollback plan without impacting production?
- What metrics and alerts would validate containment efficacy during an incident?

