questions.explanation:
## Why This Is Asked
Demonstrates ability to implement scalable, workload-driven security without NSG churn, leveraging Azure Firewall Manager, policy-based groups, Private Endpoints, and identity-based controls.

## Key Concepts
- Workload tagging and policy-based groups for dynamic segmentation
- Centralized firewall policies vs. per-VM NSGs
- Private Endpoints for service-to-service traffic
- Managed Identities for authenticating inter-service calls
- Azure Policy to enforce tagging across subscriptions
- Observability via Defender for Cloud and Log Analytics

## Code Example
```javascript
// Example: Azure Policy snippet to require workload-id tag on resources
{
  "policyRule": {
    "if": {
      "allOf": [
        { "field": "type", "in": [
          "Microsoft.Network/virtualNetworks",
          "Microsoft.Network/virtualNetworks/subnets"
        ]},
        { "field": "tags['workload-id']", "exists": "false" }
      ]
    },
    "then": { "effect": "deny" }
  },
  "name": "require-workload-id-tag",
  "properties": {
    "displayName": "Require workload-id tag on network scope",
    "policyType": "BuiltIn"
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test rollback and drift if a workload-id tag is accidentally removed?
- What metrics would you surface to confirm zero-trust posture without degrading performance?
